{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17606117","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17606117"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T13:09:31+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T13:09:31+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15897"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15897","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15897"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.26,0.26,0.26,0.05,0.16]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8588"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72075"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8588","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8588"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15897"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57545"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"3618"},{"type":"tags","id":"4929"},{"type":"tags","id":"4935"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"7607"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"20584"},{"type":"contributions","id":"20588"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72075","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/72075"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EDuring pregnancy, the placenta produces large quantities of steroid hormones. These hormones undergo various chemical modifications, including sulfation, which adds a sulfate group to the steroid molecule.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the primary physiological effect of steroid hormone sulfation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Increased water solubility while maintaining activity","Extended plasma half-life with reduced activity","Enhanced receptor binding affinity","Accelerated cellular uptake","Improved transport across cell membranes"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe sulfation of steroid hormones results in \u003Cstrong\u003Eextended plasma half-life with reduced activity\u003C/strong\u003E. This creates a stable, circulating reservoir of hormone that can be activated when needed through the action of tissue sulfatases.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreased water solubility while maintaining activity\u003C/strong\u003E - While sulfation does increase water solubility, it also inactivates the hormone\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEnhanced receptor binding affinity\u003C/strong\u003E - Sulfation prevents receptor binding by altering the structure of the steroid molecule\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAccelerated cellular uptake\u003C/strong\u003E - Sulfation actually reduces membrane permeability due to increased polarity\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EImproved transport across cell membranes\u003C/strong\u003E - The increased water solubility from sulfation reduces, rather than improves, membrane transport\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA key example is dehydroepiandrosterone sulfate (DHEA-S), which has a much longer half-life than unconjugated dehydroepiandrosterone and serves as an important precursor molecule in steroid hormone synthesis. During pregnancy, placental sulfatases can convert inactive sulfated steroids back to their active forms as needed.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Sulfation of steroid hormones increases their water solubility and plasma half-life while rendering them biologically inactive","Sulfated steroids serve as a circulating reservoir that can be converted back to active forms by tissue sulfatases","Sulfation reduces membrane permeability and prevents receptor binding of steroid hormones"],"references":["Napso T, Yong HEJ, Lopez-Tello J, Sferruzzi-Perri AN. The Role of Placental Hormones in Mediating Maternal Adaptations to Support Pregnancy and Lactation. Front Physiol. 2018 Aug 17;9:1091. doi: 10.3389/fphys.2018.01091. PMID: 30174608; PMCID: PMC6108594","Newbern D, Freemark M. Placental hormones and the control of maternal metabolism and fetal growth. Curr Opin Endocrinol Diabetes Obes. 2011 Dec;18(6):409-16. doi: 10.1097/MED.0b013e32834c800d. PMID: 21986512","Singh, V. (2022). Textbook of clinical embryology, -E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Arulkumaran, S., Ledger, W., Denny, L., \u0026 Doumouchtsis, S. (Eds.). (2019). Oxford Textbook of Obstetrics and Gynaecology. Oxford University Press","Padubidri, V. G., \u0026 Daftary, S. N. (Eds.). (2014). Shaw\u0027s Textbook of Gynecology E-book. Elsevier health sciences"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57545"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15897"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57545","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/57545"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-20T22:15:34+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-20T22:15:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8588"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72075"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name"